properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Extreme cold conditions are forecast to last for a prolonged period. Wind chill values of minus 40 or colder will continue through the coming week and next weekend. Some moderation may occur during the afternoon hours. As an Arctic airmass starts to descend southward across Alberta this weekend, this extreme cold warning will likely be expanded. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain Saturday followed by freezing rain Saturday night into Sunday. A moisture laden low from Texas will spread rain across Eastern Ontario overnight into Saturday, with most areas receiving a total of 20 to 30 mm by Saturday evening. The rain is then expected to change over to freezing rain Saturday evening as temperatures slide down to the zero degree mark. Freezing rain may last for several hours Saturday night before becoming mixed with ice pellets or a couple cm of snow Sunday. Significant ice accretion of 10 to 20 mm is possible Saturday night from the freezing rain. Brisk northerly winds Sunday are also possible. These winds coupled with ice build up on tree branches and power lines could cause a few power outages. Warnings will be issued as the event draws nearer. Travel will be impacted throughout Southern Ontario Saturday into Sunday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major low pressure system will affect the province of Quebec on Saturday and Sunday. Snowfall amounts in excess of 15 centimetres are expected. The snow is expected to begin Saturday morning over western and northern regions of the province, whereas central regions will see rain. On Sunday, precipitation will intensify and change over to snow or ice pellets over all areas. Freezing rain is also possible. Difficult travel conditions can be expected mainly as of Saturday evening. In addition, strong gusts of 60-80 km/h are expected on Sunday, possibly causing local blowing snow. There is still some uncertainty regarding the track of this system, which could impact the total amounts of snow and ice pellets. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall, combined with melting snow, is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. A soaker on tap Saturday. A moisture laden low from Texas will spread rain across Eastern Ontario overnight into Saturday, with most areas receiving a total of 20 to 30 mm by Saturday evening. The rain is then expected to change over to freezing rain Saturday evening as temperatures slide down to the zero degree mark. Since the ground is frozen, the winter rainfall warning criterion of 25 mm in 24 hours is being met. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local conservation authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry district office. Freezing rain may last for several hours Saturday night before becoming mixed with ice pellets or a couple cm of snow Sunday. Significant ice accretion of 10 to 20 mm is possible Saturday night from the freezing rain. Freezing rain warnings will likely be issued as this event draws closer. Brisk northerly winds Sunday are also possible. These winds coupled with ice build up on tree branches and power lines could cause a few power outages. Warnings will be issued as the event draws nearer. Travel will be impacted throughout Southern Ontario Saturday into Sunday. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant ice build-up due to freezing rain is expected or occurring. Ice storm Saturday afternoon and Saturday night. A moisture laden low from Texas may bring an ice storm to parts of Southern Ontario Saturday afternoon and Saturday night. Rain will turn over to freezing rain on Saturday. The changeover will firsty occur in the morning over the Bruce Peninsula then over remaining areas by noon. An extended period of freezing rain, mixed at times with ice pellets, appears likely before precipitation comes to an end on Sunday morning. An extended period of freezing rain is expected, along with ice accretion of 10 to 20 mm in many areas. Ice accretion may reach 25 mm in a few locales by Sunday morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and extremely hazardous. Extended and widespread utility outages are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
